{
  "doc_id": "51774",
  "text": "In contrast to the activation of p38 MAPK in the nuclear/ myofilament fraction, AMP-579 treatment was associated with a decrease in membrane p38 phosphorylation. Our observation of significant membrane p38 expression and activation is consistent with other reports that myocardial membranes do contain p38 MAPK [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] . It is not clear why AMP-579 decreased p38 phosphorylation in the membrane fraction before ischemia, but this was not due to translocation of p38␣ out of this compartment. Because no detergent was used in the subcellular fractionation, the membrane fraction contained caveolar membranes. These flask-shaped invaginations of the sarcolemma may play an important role in signal transduction because numerous signaling molecules, including p38 MAPK, are located in caveolae [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] . Because the caveolar fraction contains Ͻ10% of the total protein in cardiomyocytes [CITATION_5] , the effects of ischemia-reperfusion and adenosine PC on membrane p38 MAPK distribution and activation may have been underestimated.",
